VI. Acts are mixed by the accession of another act, as in giving security, and in pledge. For suretiship, if you regard the business which takes place between the surety-giver and the principal debtor, is for the most part a commission: if you regard the business be- tween the creditor and the surety—giver, who receives nothing, it is an act merely liberal: but because this liberal act is added to an onerose contract, it is reckoned with such contracts. So the giving of a pledge seems to be a liberal act, by which the detention of a thing is conceded3 but this also takes its nature from the contract which is thus supplied with a security.

VII. All acts useful to others, with the exception of merely beneficial acts, are called Contracts.

VIII. In Contracts, nature requires equality, and in such a way that, from inequahty, he who has the worse share, acquires a right. This equality consists partly in the act, partly in the matter concern- ing which the act is, and in the acts both precedent and principal.
